				\begin{document}$$N_{\text{defect}} \, = \,2\varepsilon_{0} \varepsilon_{r} V_{\text{TFL}} /eL^{2}$$\end{document}where εr is the relative permittivity of perovskite material (εr = 32) [9, 59], ε0 is the vacuum permittivity (ε0 = 8.85 × 10−12 F m−1), e is the electron charge, and L is the thickness of perovskite film (L = 800 nm) in the devices [60]. The value of VTFL decreased from 0.73 to 0.60 V after performing the aging treatment; the estimated defect density of 4.97 × 1015 cm−3 for the LTAG-based device was lower than that for the control reference (6.05 × 1015 cm−3). This finding suggests that effective self-passivation had occurred and, thus, the number of traps had decreased. This phenomenon contributed to the observed higher values of Voc, which led to the higher PCEs, of the LTAG-based solar cells [61].
